DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The conceptual analysis of tradition remains surprisingly under-developed
in contemporary analytic philosophy, despite tradition's centrality to
social and political philosophy. The domain divides into three main
approaches: (1) Lewis-inspired convention theory that treats traditions
as coordination equilibria; (2) social ontology approaches examining
traditions as practices, norms, or institutions; and (3) direct
conceptual analysis attempting to define tradition and distinguish it
from related phenomena.

Key debates center on: whether traditions are essentially temporally
extended (requiring transmission across generations); whether they are
primarily normative (prescribing action) or descriptive (patterns of
behavior); and how to distinguish traditions from customs, conventions,
habits, and institutions. Beckstein (2017) provides the most systematic
recent treatment, arguing that traditions must exhibit both continuity
and authentic continuation criteria. Shils (1981) remains foundational
despite being sociological rather than strictly philosophical. The SEP
entries on convention (Lewis, Marmor), social norms (Bicchieri), and
social institutions (Searle, Miller) provide rich conceptual resources
but rarely address tradition directly.

Recent work shows renewed interest in tradition's role in practical
rationality (MacIntyre's influence persists) and in political philosophy
(debates over conservatism, multiculturalism). However, there remains
no consensus "theory of tradition" comparable to Lewis on convention or
Searle on institutions.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain provides essential conceptual foundations for understanding
what traditions ARE before investigating their value or breakdown. The
distinction between traditions and mere customs/conventions matters
critically: if traditions require authentic continuation and meaningful
transmission (not just behavioral repetition), then questions of
degeneration become more tractable. The temporal extension requirement
connects to issues of tradition identity over time—crucial for asking
when a tradition has "failed" versus merely evolved.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Surprisingly little work directly engages the ontology of traditions.
Most philosophical work treats traditions as examples within broader
theories (of convention, practice, social ontology) rather than
analyzing the concept itself. The relationship between tradition and
temporal extension needs more rigorous treatment. Very limited engagement
with cross-cultural conceptions of tradition beyond Western philosophy.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Begin with Lewis/convention theory to establish baseline (traditions as
regularity + common knowledge), then examine why this is insufficient
(Beckstein's critique). Use Shils for typology and MacIntyre for
practice-based alternative. SEP entries provide the broader conceptual
landscape (institutions, practices, norms) within which traditions sit.
The synthesis should emphasize that conceptual clarity here is
prerequisite to normative analysis in other domains.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Convention-theoretic: 4 papers - Traditions as coordination equilibria (Lewis, Marmor)
- Practice-based: 5 papers - Traditions as practices requiring transmission (MacIntyre, Beckstein)
- Social ontology: 6 papers - Traditions as social institutions/norms (Searle, Tuomela, Miller)
====================================================================
}

