This domain examines how traditions function within political theory,
particularly regarding political authority, legitimacy, constitutions,
and democratic governance. A central tension runs through the literature
between traditionalist and constitutionalist approaches: traditionalists
(exemplified by Burke and Oakeshott) emphasize inherited practices and
institutional wisdom, while constitutionalists focus on formal legal
limits and rational principles. Recent work explores how constitutional
traditions differ from cultural traditions, how civic republican
traditions understand political participation, and whether democratic
self-governance can be grounded in or reconciled with inherited
traditions. The literature also addresses founding myths, constitutional
identity, and the relationship between tradition and reform.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses how political traditions ground authority
and legitimacy, providing essential context for understanding when and
why political traditions succeed or fail. The tension between tradition
and rational reform illuminates conditions under which traditions
degenerate. Work on constitutional traditions reveals how formal
political structures depend on informal traditional practices.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
